---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'How to Buy Baijiu Outside China Without Getting Misled';
const description = 'A practical overseas buying guide for baijiu: channels, labels, importer checks, pricing signals, gift boxes, and common red flags.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <header class="article-header">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Overseas Buying</p>
      <h1>How to Buy Baijiu Outside China</h1>
      <p class="lede">Outside China, the hardest part is not finding baijiu. It is knowing whether the bottle, seller, price, and story make sense.</p>
    </div>
  </header>
  <section class="content">
    <article>
      <p>Baijiu buying outside China is uneven. Some cities have excellent specialist stores and importers. Other markets have only a few dusty bottles, confusing gift boxes, or marketplace listings with weak product information. Your first filter should be trust, not decoration.</p>

      <h2>Check the Channel First</h2>
      <p>Prefer licensed retailers, known importers, established Asian spirits shops, and restaurants or distributors that can explain what they sell. Be more careful with anonymous marketplace sellers, private resellers, and listings built around "rare," "vintage," or "limited" language without documentation.</p>

      <h2>What To Inspect</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Check</th><th>Good sign</th><th>Red flag</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Importer label</td><td>Clear importer or distributor details for your market</td><td>No local compliance information on an imported bottle</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Seller knowledge</td><td>Can explain aroma type, producer, ABV, and intended use</td><td>Only talks about price, gift value, or status</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Price</td><td>Consistent with other reliable sellers</td><td>Much cheaper than market level for a famous premium bottle</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Packaging</td><td>Clean, consistent, not the main sales argument</td><td>Heavy box, vague certificate, little liquid information</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Product name</td><td>Specific brand and product line</td><td>Confusing use of a famous group name without clarity</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Do Not Overpay for Mystery</h2>
      <p>Overseas buyers often overpay because they cannot read Chinese labels or judge the difference between a core flagship bottle and a related development product. If a listing leans heavily on "official," "special edition," "aged," or "collector" language, slow down and verify what product line it actually belongs to.</p>

      <h2>Best Buying Path for Beginners</h2>
      <p>Start with a bottle that has enough information to compare: aroma type, ABV, producer, importer, and intended drinking context. A moderate bottle from a reliable channel teaches more than a mysterious premium-looking bottle from a weak seller.</p>

      <section class="faq">
        <h2>FAQ</h2>
        <h3>Where should I buy baijiu overseas?</h3>
        <p>Start with licensed retailers, reputable online spirits shops, known importers, and specialist Asian alcohol stores. Trust and traceability matter more than the lowest price.</p>
        <h3>Are marketplace baijiu listings safe?</h3>
        <p>Some may be legitimate, but risk is higher when seller identity, import route, storage, and product line are unclear.</p>
        <h3>What is the biggest beginner buying mistake?</h3>
        <p>Buying a famous-looking bottle without understanding whether it is authentic, fairly priced, and suitable for the occasion.</p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
